      <!-- Star 5 (empty) -->
      <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-slate-300" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20">
        <path d="M9.049 2.927c.3-.921 1.603-.921 1.902 0l1.07 3.292a1 1 0 00.95.69h3.462c.969 0 1.371 1.24.588 1.81l-2.8 2.034a1 1 0 00-.364 1.118l1.07 3.292c.3.921-.755 1.688-1.54 1.118l-2.8-2.034a1 1 0 00-1.175 0l-2.8 2.034c-.784.57-1.838-.197-1.539-1.118l1.07-3.292a1 1 0 00-.364-1.118L2.98 8.72c-.783-.57-.38-1.81.588-1.81h3.461a1 1 0 00.951-.69l1.07-3.292z" />
      </svg>
    </div>
    <span class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy">3.3 / 5</span>
  </div>

  <!-- Summary Verdict -->
  <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-8">
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
      <strong>The bottom line:</strong> Sakai remains a functional open-source LMS for higher education, but declining adoption and community activity make it a questionable choice for new implementations. Existing Sakai users can continue operating, but institutions evaluating options should consider Canvas, Moodle, or Blackboard Ultra for their larger ecosystems and continued investment. Sakai's era as a leading platform has passed.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Who this is for -->
  <p class="text-slate-600 mb-8 leading-relaxed">
    This review is written for higher education IT leaders, CIOs, and academic technology directors evaluating LMS options or managing existing Sakai installations. If you're considering Sakai for a new deployment or planning a migration away from it, this will help inform your decision.
  </p>

  <!-- Key Takeaways -->
  <KeyTakeaways items={[
    "Sakai is a community-developed open-source LMS governed by the Apereo Foundation.",
    "Market share has declined significantly as institutions migrate to Canvas, Blackboard Ultra, and Moodle.",
    "Still in use at major universities including Duke, NYU, and University of Michigan.",
    "Development continues but at slower pace than competing platforms.",
    "Not recommended for new implementations—better alternatives exist with stronger futures.",
    "Existing users should plan migration strategies as community support continues to shrink."
  ]} />

  <!-- What is Sakai? -->
  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">What is Sakai?</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Sakai is an open-source Learning Management System developed specifically for higher education. First released in 2005, it emerged from a collaboration between Indiana University, MIT, Stanford, UC Berkeley, University of Michigan, and the Open Knowledge Initiative. The project aimed to create an enterprise-class LMS alternative to commercial platforms.
    </p>
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      The Apereo Foundation, a non-profit supporting open-source software for education, now governs Sakai. Development is community-driven, with participating institutions contributing code, testing, and documentation. This governance model ensures the platform remains free and institutionally controlled, unlike vendor-owned alternatives.
    </p>
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
      Sakai's peak adoption occurred in the early 2010s when it was a genuine competitor to Blackboard and emerging Canvas. Since then, Canvas has captured most of the North American higher education market, while Moodle dominates open-source deployments. Sakai's user base has contracted significantly, though it maintains a committed core of institutional users.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Who is Sakai Best For? -->
  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">Who is Sakai Best For?</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
      Honest assessment suggests Sakai is rarely the best choice for new implementations. However, specific scenarios exist where it remains viable:
    </p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-4">
      <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy mb-2">Existing Sakai Institutions</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Universities with deep Sakai customization, integrated tools, and trained staff may find migration costs exceed staying put. For these institutions, continuing with Sakai while monitoring the platform's trajectory is reasonable.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy mb-2">Strong Technical Teams</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Institutions with robust Java development capabilities can maintain and extend Sakai independently. The open-source nature allows complete control for organizations with resources to exercise it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy mb-2">Specific Collaborative Research</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Sakai's project sites and research collaboration tools have historically served academic research teams. Groups with established workflows in these tools may have migration resistance.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy mb-2">Philosophical Commitment</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Institutions prioritizing non-profit governance and complete institutional control over vendor relationships. Sakai's Apereo Foundation governance is genuinely community-based.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Core Capabilities -->
  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">Core Capabilities</h2>

    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy mt-6 mb-3">Course Sites</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Sakai provides standard LMS course functionality: content management, assignment submission, gradebook, quizzes, and announcements. The interface is functional but dated compared to modern platforms. Instructors can organize materials, create assessments, and manage student submissions through familiar workflows.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy mt-6 mb-3">Project Sites</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Beyond courses, Sakai offers project sites for research groups, committees, and administrative collaboration. These sites include document sharing, discussion forums, wikis, and scheduling tools. This functionality was innovative for its time but is now standard in most collaboration platforms.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy mt-6 mb-3">Assessment Tools</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      The Tests & Quizzes tool supports various question types, randomization, and grading workflows. While functional, it lacks the sophistication of dedicated assessment platforms or newer LMS engines. High-stakes testing and advanced analytics are not Sakai's strengths.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy mt-6 mb-3">Portfolio Tools</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Sakai includes portfolio functionality for student work collection and reflection. This feature has been valuable for capstone programs and assessment of learning outcomes. However, dedicated portfolio platforms now offer more polished experiences.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy mt-6 mb-3">Integration Capabilities</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Sakai supports LTI (Learning Tools Interoperability) for external tool integration and has APIs for custom development. Institutions can connect third-party tools and build custom extensions. However, the integration ecosystem is smaller than Canvas or Moodle.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Key Strengths -->
  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">Key Strengths</h2>

    <div class="space-y-5">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy mb-1">Institutional Control</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
          No vendor lock-in, no licensing fees, and complete control over data and customization. Universities can modify Sakai to match specific workflows without vendor permission or annual contracts.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy mb-1">Community Governance</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
          The Apereo Foundation governance ensures Sakai serves educational interests rather than shareholder value. Decisions about features and roadmap involve the institutions using the platform.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy mb-1">Project Collaboration</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
          Project sites provide flexible collaboration spaces for research, committees, and cross-departmental work. These tools extend beyond course delivery into academic collaboration.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy mb-1">Proven at Scale</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
          Major research universities have run Sakai for years with large student populations. The platform handles scale when properly deployed and maintained.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy mb-1">No Licensing Costs</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
          Free software means budget can be directed toward hosting, customization, and support rather than vendor licenses. For budget-constrained institutions, this matters.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Where Sakai May Not Be the Best Fit -->
  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">Where Sakai May Not Be the Best Fit</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Sakai's decline reflects real limitations. Here is where it falls short:
    </p>

    <div class="space-y-5">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy mb-1">New Implementations</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
          Starting fresh with Sakai in 2026 is difficult to justify. Canvas, Moodle, and Blackboard Ultra offer larger communities, better support, more modern interfaces, and clearer futures. The risk of investing in a declining platform is substantial.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy mb-1">Modern User Experience</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
          Sakai's interface feels dated compared to contemporary platforms. Students and faculty accustomed to modern web applications encounter friction with Sakai's design paradigms from an earlier era.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy mb-1">Mobile Experience</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
          Mobile access exists but lags behind native mobile apps from Canvas and Blackboard. Mobile-first students expect seamless phone and tablet experiences that Sakai struggles to deliver.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy mb-1">Shrinking Community</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
          Each year, fewer institutions use Sakai. This means fewer contributed improvements, fewer community resources, fewer third-party integrations, and less collective knowledge. The network effects work in reverse.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy mb-1">Technical Overhead</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
          Self-hosting Sakai requires significant technical expertise. Java application servers, database management, and upgrade processes demand skilled IT staff. Smaller institutions often lack these resources.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Pricing Overview -->
  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">Pricing Overview</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Sakai software is free under the Educational Community License Version 2.0. Costs are limited to infrastructure, support, and any customization or integration work.
    </p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-slate-200 mb-4">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="bg-navy text-white">
            <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold">Cost Category</th>
            <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold">Typical Range</th>
            <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold">Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="bg-white border-t border-slate-200">
            <td class="py-3 px-4 font-medium text-navy">Software License</td>
            <td class="py-3 px-4 text-slate-600">$0</td>
            <td class="py-3 px-4 text-slate-600">Open source under ECL 2.0</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-slate-50 border-t border-slate-200">
            <td class="py-3 px-4 font-medium text-navy">Self-Hosted Infrastructure</td>
            <td class="py-3 px-4 text-slate-600">Varies widely</td>
            <td class="py-3 px-4 text-slate-600">Depends on institution size and redundancy needs</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-white border-t border-slate-200">
            <td class="py-3 px-4 font-medium text-navy">Commercial Support</td>
            <td class="py-3 px-4 text-slate-600">Quote-based</td>
            <td class="py-3 px-4 text-slate-600">Available from third-party providers</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-slate-50 border-t border-slate-200">
            <td class="py-3 px-4 font-medium text-navy">Migration Costs</td>
            <td class="py-3 px-4 text-slate-600">Significant</td>
            <td class="py-3 px-4 text-slate-600">Moving away from Sakai requires substantial investment</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p class="text-sm text-slate-500">
      Total cost of ownership depends primarily on whether institutions self-host or use commercial support services.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- How Sakai Compares -->
  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">How Sakai Compares</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Here is how Sakai stacks up against other higher education LMS options:
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable
      headers={["Sakai", "Canvas", "Blackboard Ultra", "Moodle", "D2L Brightspace"]}
      highlight={0}
      rows={[
        { feature: "License", values: ["Open source (ECL)", "Commercial", "Commercial", "Open source (GPL)", "Commercial"] },
        { feature: "Market Position", values: ["Declining", "Dominant (US)", "Established", "Strong open source", "Strong (Canada/global)"] },
        { feature: "User Experience", values: ["Dated", "Modern", "Modern (rebuilt)", "Configurable", "Modern"] },
        { feature: "Mobile Apps", values: ["Limited", "Excellent", "Good", "Via plugins", "Good"] },
        { feature: "Community Size", values: ["Shrinking", "Massive", "Large", "Massive", "Moderate"] },
        { feature: "Support Model", values: ["Community/3rd party", "Commercial", "Commercial", "Community/commercial", "Commercial"] },
        { feature: "Best For", values: ["Existing users only", "Most universities", "Enterprise needs", "Technical control", "K-12/higher ed hybrid"] }
      ]}
    />
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <LeadFormModal
    variant="inline"
    ctaTitle="Considering your LMS options or planning a migration?"
    ctaDescription="Get a personalized recommendation based on your institution size, technical resources, and academic requirements."
    ctaButtonText="Get My Recommendation"
  />

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <FAQ items={faqItems} />

  <!-- Related Pages -->
  <RelatedPages pages={[
    { title: "Canvas Review", href: "/reviews/canvas", description: "The dominant LMS in North American higher education with modern interface and strong mobile apps." },
    { title: "Moodle Review", href: "/reviews/moodle", description: "The world's most popular open-source LMS with massive community and extensive customization." },
    { title: "Blackboard Review", href: "/reviews/blackboard", description: "Enterprise LMS with long history and comprehensive feature set for higher education." },
    { title: "Best LMS for Higher Education", href: "/guides/best-lms-higher-ed", description: "Complete guide to choosing the right LMS for your university or college." }
  ]} />

</ReviewLayout>